I suspected that this idea of AIDS becoming increasingly heterosexual was overblown so I looked at these stats:http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/stats/hasr140...anceReport.pdfLooking at the 30 areas in the country where cases are reported, over 1999-2002 (most recent years availalbe) new cases every year were going up more from male-males contacts compared to female hetersexual contact, and new male hetersexual cases went DOWN a tiny bit between 1999 and 2002. The trends are different if we look at national estimates (I can't figure out why the whole country is supposed to be going in the opposite direction of the 30 areas where data is actually reported.) Over the 1998-2002 5 year period, the average new cases went up 83 cases for male-male contact, it went up 181 cases for male heterosexual contact, and 235 additional cases each year for female heterosexual contact. With around 42,000 new AIDS cases each year, the slightly higher numbers for heterosexuals is not very significant. As of 2002, 45% of the total new cases were from male-male contact (or not being able to tell if it was male-male sex or sharing needles). At this pace, heterosexuals are NEVER going to catch up and contract AIDS at the rates  homosexuals do. A tiny group of Americans produces 45% of all new cases; heterosexual rates will never be that high. Another way of looking at it is to calculate what percentage of people are living with HIV/AIDS. The CDC doesn't give those numbers (that I could see) so I calculated and found that it is 4.97% of male homosexuals, and .09% for everyone else. That .09% is never ever going to catch up.While the risk of infection is 55 times higher for a male homosexual (4.97%/.09%) than everyone else, it is still a small minority of homosexuals that suffer from the disaese. Morevover, the rate of infection for lesbians is very low.
