I'm interested in this question of the typical homosexual lifestyle, so I started an analysis of General Social Survey data--a nationally representative sample of Americans conducted every year by the U. of Chicago:http://webapp.icpsr.umich.edu/GSS/I looked to see if gay men, lesbians, and bisexuals differed on aspects of lifestyle I ran across. Contrary to earlier posts, I found that homosexual men are less likely to smoke. Lesbians and bisexual men were the groups who smoked the most.I looked to see what percent of people hang out in bars almost every night. Bisexuals were the most likely; gay and hetero men were in the middle; lesbians and hetero women were least likely to. I looked to see what percent of people were: romantically involved; lived together; and were happy in their relationship. Both hetero groups and the bisexual men and especially lesbians were the most likely to be involved, and gay men and bisexual women were the least likely. A high percentage of gay men and lesbians lived with their romantic partner; the bisexual groups were least likely, with heteros in the middle. All groups were very likely to be happy in their relationships.So these numbers don't show instability or unhealthy lifestyles among gay men and lesbians. It does look like about half of lesbians smoke, but the number of respondents was small, so this estimate may be crude. The bisexual tended to show more instability; this was probably due to the fact that the bi's tended to be younger. The only potentially negative aspect of these findings is that most gay men and lesbians who say they are romantically involved also say they are living with their partner, so this apparently makes a question about being romantically involved comparable to asking that of heteros, and thus provides evidence that the conclusion that hetero relationships tend to last longer than homosexual ones is based on comparable groups. Actually, according to this survey, you capture a higher percentage of casual relationships among the heteros when you ask, "Are you involved?"
